\begin_layout Section
Physical Biochemical Relationships
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before delving into our simple models, we'll summarize the thermodynamic
 relationships that we will cover.
 We are starting here for two reasons.
 First, it looks imprressive: by the end of this document you will hopefully
 have a handle on the ideas that these (potentially intimidating) equations
 capture.
 Second, this list provides a way to cross-reference the simple models we
 will present against the actual equations and language used by practicing
 physical biochemists.
 So, we begin:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\emph on
probabilistic definition of entropy 
\emph default
(also known as the 
\emph on
Shannon Entropy
\emph default
):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=-R\sum_{i=1}^{W}p_{i}ln\left(p_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is entropy, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 state, 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the number of states, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the gas constant.
 If all states have the same probability, this simplifies to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=Rln\left(W\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Counting statistics
\emph default
.
 The probability of seeing 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 out of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 molecules in a state with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\binom{n}{k}p^{k}\left(1-p\right)^{n-k}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{k}$
\end_inset

 notation is pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and means, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How many combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 molecules are possible when drawing from 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 total?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\emph on
thermodynamic definition of entropy
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\frac{q_{rev}}{T}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{rev}$
\end_inset

 is the reversible heat of a reaction and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the absolute temperature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The microscopic meaning of heat (
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

), enthalpy (
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

) and free energy (
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The spontaneity of a reaction is determined by the change in enthalpy (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H$
\end_inset

) and entropy (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G=\Delta H-T\Delta S.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Inter-relationships between 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{eq}$
\end_inset

, and reaction rates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G=-RTln\left(K_{eq}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{eq}$
\end_inset

 is the equilibrium constant for the reaction.
 This can also be written in terms of reaction rates (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{forward}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{reverse}$
\end_inset

) and equilibrium concentrations (
\begin_inset Formula $[products]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[reactants]$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{eq}=\frac{k_{forward}}{k_{reverse}}=\frac{[products]}{[reactants]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First-order rate laws of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d[product]}{dt}=k_{forward}[rectant]-k_{reverse}[product]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The relative probabilities of states using 
\emph on
Boltzmann weights
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{A}=\left(\frac{e^{-E_{A}/RT}}{\sum_{i}e^{-E_{i}/RT}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of state 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of state 
\begin_inset Formula $i.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How thermodynamic measurements provide insight into molecular mechanism,
 with a focus on heat capacity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{p}=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial T}\right)_{P}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta H(T)=\Delta H(T_{ref})+\Delta C_{p}(T-T_{ref})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S(T)=\Delta S(T_{ref})+\Delta C_{p}ln\left(\frac{T}{T_{ref}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the heat capacity and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ref}$
\end_inset

 is a chosen reference temperature.
 
\end_layout

